    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1240029405" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1240029405" />
    <a title="Czarny Pies" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/29160274-czarny-pies"><img alt="Czarny Pies" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1400687408p2/29160274.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1240029405?book_show_action=true">Mar 29, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Czarny Pies" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Czarny Pies" href="/user/show/29160274-czarny-pies">Czarny Pies</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/29160274-czarny-pies?shelf=polish-lit">polish-lit</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1240029405" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8541202372206020038">This book is piffle, highly entertaining piffle albeit, but piffle. Written and published during the martial law period when the Solidarity movement was driven underground and many of its leaders were in jail, the author who profoundly misreads the true political lay of the land decides to settle accounts with those intellectuals of Poland who first flirted with Solidarity and then went scurrying back to their regular communist patrons once the government declared martial law and began jailing S</span>
  <span id="freeText8541202372206020038" style="display:none">This book is piffle, highly entertaining piffle albeit, but piffle. Written and published during the martial law period when the Solidarity movement was driven underground and many of its leaders were in jail, the author who profoundly misreads the true political lay of the land decides to settle accounts with those intellectuals of Poland who first flirted with Solidarity and then went scurrying back to their regular communist patrons once the government declared martial law and began jailing Solidarity's blue collar.<br /><br />Konwicki clearly did not understand that Solidarity had the moral,organizational and financial resources to weather the storm. What he did understand was how thin the support for Solidarity was amongst his fellow intellectual. Thus when the clamp down came, the intellectuals were relieved as much as disappointed. Konwicki thus entertains his readers with their complex and sophisticated explanations of why it was in everyone's interest that they support the tough-minded communist regime rather than paying the dreadful consequences of continuing to resist. Konwicki's book is hilarious from start to finish. <br /><br />I found particularly comical his attack on an internationally renowned movie director who appears to be modelled on Andrzej Wajda. The internationally renowned movie director describes his life in this way: "Look I started with a film that slandered the Home Army, that is the very milieu I came from, then I made a film glorifying the ill-fated Home Army. When the country was wasting away in a stupor, oppressed by a situation that was half occupation, half freedom, I was making psychological films. I took a little of this and a little of that. I was trying to keep up with certain world trends. ... I always thought that I was doing what could be done at a given moment. But look closer at the consistent thrust of my ideas and statements. I was carrying out the Party Line in Technicolor. I rolled along with it from one error to the next."<br /><br />The problem is that in writing his brilliant satire of the intelligentsia, Konwicki missed what was really happening in Poland. Solidarity had a strong underground organization. The Catholic Church was smuggling money into Poland to support the families of the jailed workers. Solidarity's working class members simply kept on saying their rosaries and waiting for the luck to turn which it did. <br /><br />Ultimately, Konwicki's only fault was that he moved with those who had conceded defeat at Solidarity's first set back and were not terribly distressed by what they though the was the end of Solidarity. However, most of Poland was still fighting on and highly confident in their ultimate success. Minor Apocalypse certainly describes what was going on in one segment of Polish Society during the Solidarity era but misses what was happening everywhere else. It gives the reader the sideshow but misses on the big event.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8541202372206020038" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

