  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3275609884" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3275609884" />
    <a title="Chase" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/49346830-chase"><img alt="Chase" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1589155070p2/49346830.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3275609884?book_show_action=true">Apr 17, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Chase" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Chase" href="/user/show/49346830-chase">Chase</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3275609884" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7693130931522155181">This week in books that make you want to put a revolver to the roof of your mouth, we have a classic piece of Polish dissident literature, aptly entitled, A Minor Apocalypse. Written by the legendary WWII guerilla fighter turned film director and novelist, Tadeusz Konwicki. It’s a book filled to the brim with surreal set pieces, doused heavily in the Polish proclivity for melodrama, and its nihilistic streams of verbose prose-poetry.<br/><br/>The overarching narrative that ties all these disparate element</span>
  <span id="freeText7693130931522155181" style="display:none">This week in books that make you want to put a revolver to the roof of your mouth, we have a classic piece of Polish dissident literature, aptly entitled, A Minor Apocalypse. Written by the legendary WWII guerilla fighter turned film director and novelist, Tadeusz Konwicki. It’s a book filled to the brim with surreal set pieces, doused heavily in the Polish proclivity for melodrama, and its nihilistic streams of verbose prose-poetry.<br /><br />The overarching narrative that ties all these disparate elements together is rather simple…A dissident, washed up writer (also named Konwicki) is awoken one morning by two old friends, who are involved in the resistance movement for the liberation of communist Poland. It’s the day of a large political gathering, government functionaries from across the Soviet Union are visiting Warsaw to celebrate the anniversary of communism in Poland. Thus the pair approach Konwicki with a proposition. They want him to use his status (as a representative of the Polish intellectual elite) to make a political statement. A rather incendiary one. In a word, self-immolation…In the front of the ministry for culture televised for the entire country to watch.<br /><br />The rest of the novel features Konwicki traipsing around the nightmarish dystopian shitshow of late-70s Warsaw pondering this proposition. Along the way he encounters various dignitaries, crack-pots, writers, old friends, poets, film directors, government torture rooms, underground passage ways, Russian girls with a lust for life, and lapses into frighteningly abysmal moments of interiority and madness…In totality the books sports a frenetic and batshit crazy kinda energy, not unlike the films of Andrzej Żuławski (of Possession, and On the Silver Globe fame) a man whose career Konwicki inadvertently helped establish.<br /><br />Thematically, the novel addresses the illusion of freedom, the role and insignificance of the individual in relation to acts of resistance, the hostile and deferring nature of hope, the godlessness of post-WWII europe, the political quagmire of 20th century Polish history, a scathing portrait of Polish dissident art and artists and their ultimate failure to alter the course of this history. Its a book in which I'm kinda astounded Konwicki was able to write...There isn't the least attempt at cloaking the fury and invective that he exposes toward soviet society or humanity in general...And while it was published in samizdat, the very fact that Konwicki was still able to draw on government funds to make films immediately afterward is even more perplexing. The censors have a mind of their own I suppose.<br /><br />Though the strangest thing about this book, is the relative lack of narrative contextualization for the various actions and scenes that pass one right after the other. It has a very PKD-like amateurish kinda sensibility about it (that I find somewhat inspiring). I think this feeling stems from the low amount of descriptive energy put into establishing the setting within each respective scene, and the while prose is laser sharp and amiable to read, this lack of grounding in place, gives the book a rootless and abstract rendering within the mind of the reader. And the middle section of the novel centering on the sacking of a government dinner party, could’ve been greatly trimmed…Though none of these stylistic quirks really derailed the experience for me. In totality I’d recommend this novel to people who are fans of Polish cinema, and literary surrealism and weird fiction in general.<br />4.5/5.</span>
  <a data-text-id="7693130931522155181" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


