<div id="review_2664796118" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2664796118" />
    <a title="Adam" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1083458-adam"><img alt="Adam" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1545315869p2/1083458.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2664796118?book_show_action=true">Jan 13, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Adam" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Adam" href="/user/show/1083458-adam">Adam</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 394724429" href="/book/show/29937360-a-minor-apocalypse">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2664796118" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2696970470908761614">A marvelous coming-of-death novel (can we coin <i>Todskommtroman</i>?), death of a person, a vision, a nation, ideals all around going up in smoke. The spurious measurement of the book against &quot;actually existing Poland&quot; misses the point entirely: he&apos;s a Polish writer, duh, but not only is politics ipso facto a global matter, it occurs within a historical context, the relevance of which interpretation is supposed to highlight rather than smugly confine to way-back-when-over-there. The--ahem--burning que</span>
  <span id="freeText2696970470908761614" style="display:none">A marvelous coming-of-death novel (can we coin <i>Todskommtroman</i>?), death of a person, a vision, a nation, ideals all around going up in smoke. The spurious measurement of the book against "actually existing Poland" misses the point entirely: he's a Polish writer, duh, but not only is politics ipso facto a global matter, it occurs within a historical context, the relevance of which interpretation is supposed to highlight rather than smugly confine to way-back-when-over-there. The--ahem--burning question is on one level simply that of the historical relationship of the individual and the state (or The Cause), but on another more intimate level it asks what is worth dying for when the universe seems meaningless. It was both more lyrical and more absurd than I anticipated, equal parts "cry of the soul" and wry look askance at folly and hubris. The narrator feebly touts his free will at every stop on this crooked Via Dolorosa, all the while being drawn inexorably to the fateful site of self-immolation as a duty and a privilege, a punishment for failing and a reprieve from trying ever again. A pleasurable, ruminative read, I leave two quotes here I think are emblematic of the tone of widespread ruin: <br><br>"A lazy peal of thunder rolled from one end of the city to the other. The wind drove the balcony doors groaning open. I would have closed them but the handle had come off."<br><br>"Somehow everyone is satisfied with the places fate and the chain of genes has assigned them. And they modestly go about doing the bidding of the Great Entropy. But I feel offended by fate, my limitations, God. I desire something which I cannot do, I dream of what cannot be. I am drowning in the sixty liters of my own poisonous fluids, me, a flawed, two-legged mammal."<br><br>Once upon a time we could "wake the sleepers with a wild cry," right...?<br> <img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/photos/1547417746p8/3766919.jpg" width="399" height="598" alt="description" class="gr-hostedUserImg"></span>
  <a data-text-id="2696970470908761614" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


