    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3208591" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3208591" />
    <a title="Rachel Denham" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/67318-rachel-denham"><img alt="Rachel Denham" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1184793439p2/67318.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3208591?book_show_action=true">Jul 18, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rachel Denham" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rachel Denham" href="/user/show/67318-rachel-denham">Rachel Denham</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3208591" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer385046522467682340">I would definitely give this book 4.5-5 stars and recommend it to anyone interested in Eastern European/Polish literature. My only complaint is that I wished I could have read it all at one time because it chronicles one day in this man&apos;s life so there weren&apos;t any chapters, which made it somewhat difficult to come back and to understand everything that had been going on beforehand.<br/><br/>I&apos;m sure that there was a lot that I didn&apos;t understand, having never studied Polish History in-depth. Basically, all</span>
  <span id="freeText385046522467682340" style="display:none">I would definitely give this book 4.5-5 stars and recommend it to anyone interested in Eastern European/Polish literature. My only complaint is that I wished I could have read it all at one time because it chronicles one day in this man's life so there weren't any chapters, which made it somewhat difficult to come back and to understand everything that had been going on beforehand.<br /><br />I'm sure that there was a lot that I didn't understand, having never studied Polish History in-depth. Basically, all I knew about Poland came from learning about the histories of its invaders (ie. Germany, the Soviet Union.) If you have a basic understanding of Poland's situation in the 20th century, though (I don't think you really need to understand anything beforehand in order to get the book, though I'm sure that it helps), you should be able to follow the book.<br /><br />The writing (even though it is through an English translation) is very rich and concise. For the most part, the book was easy to follow along, yet there still remained that distinctness that separates it from Western literature: the understandings of life and death are so different from our own, and even though a part of me (as a Westerner) didn't understand his reasonings, another part of me did. <br /><br />There were some parts that were lagging, but everything ties in together very nicely in the end. Even though the ending of the book is already laid out within the first 15 pages, the final scenes are still surprising: you know what's going to happen, yet when it finally does, you're shocked that it actually occurred. </span>
  <a data-text-id="385046522467682340" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


