<span id="freeTextContainer8407492188521916879">A rather Kafkaesque type story. In it, an over the hill writer is convinced to set himself on fire in front of the Communist party headquarters as a protest against oppressive government control. He is somewhat reluctant but agrees to do it only with the provision that he may back out. So, the book tells of his activities that day leading up to the event. He has many encounters with various people including the police, as well as many of his friends and associates. He even falls in love. All thi</span>
  <span id="freeText8407492188521916879" style="display:none">A rather Kafkaesque type story. In it, an over the hill writer is convinced to set himself on fire in front of the Communist party headquarters as a protest against oppressive government control. He is somewhat reluctant but agrees to do it only with the provision that he may back out. So, the book tells of his activities that day leading up to the event. He has many encounters with various people including the police, as well as many of his friends and associates. He even falls in love. All this time he seems rather detached and unconcerned about his fate. It's an interesting premise but it just seemed to fall short of its potential.</span>
