<div id="review_798226126" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/798226126" />
    <a title="Steve Anderson" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/24684338-steve-anderson"><img alt="Steve Anderson" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1381874363p2/24684338.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/798226126?book_show_action=true">Dec 23, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Steve Anderson" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Steve Anderson" href="/user/show/24684338-steve-anderson">Steve Anderson</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer798226126" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer1521798727696821274">Somber and thought-provoking are the two words that come to mind reading Tadeusz Konwicki’s novel. While not knowing a lot about Polish history, I have spent a few months in Poland and heard stories about life under communism. This novel is a fascinating look at Poland when, according to the author, the opposition and the government were more partners than adversaries.<br/><br/>It’s also the story of an older man’s perspective on a life time of struggle and compliance. The story, which takes place in one </span>
  <span id="freeText1521798727696821274" style="display:none">Somber and thought-provoking are the two words that come to mind reading Tadeusz Konwicki’s novel. While not knowing a lot about Polish history, I have spent a few months in Poland and heard stories about life under communism. This novel is a fascinating look at Poland when, according to the author, the opposition and the government were more partners than adversaries.<br /><br />It’s also the story of an older man’s perspective on a life time of struggle and compliance. The story, which takes place in one day, takes the reader through everything from basic plumbing problems faced by Poles in everyday life, random stops by the secret police, not so random stops by opposition members, to critiques of artists and their relationship with the rulers. <br /><br />Each page is also packed with meaning. Physics, biology, spirituality can all be interwoven in a passage in a way that makes you want to come back to that page just so you can spend a day or two thinking about its import. I can’t stand that type of writing when it seems to be showing off by the author. With Konwicki’s character, it seems natural and appropriate.<br /><br />Is resistance futile? Can a person’s death have a larger meaning? The book doesn’t come down with a definitive answer; instead, it serves up a day long feast of a search for that answer.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="1521798727696821274" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


