<div id="review_1263067411" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1263067411" />
    <a title="Angel 一匹狼" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/25600796-angel"><img alt="Angel 一匹狼" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1438533669p2/25600796.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1263067411?book_show_action=true">Apr 24, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Angel 一匹狼" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Angel 一匹狼" href="/user/show/25600796-angel">Angel 一匹狼</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1263067411" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3499391149117837836">This is a very interesting book, even though I just rated it with 2 stars. It was written around a very important period of Polish history (last century&apos;s eighties), and it is a very interesting and quite realistic (taking everything into account) view of the Communist Poland. All characters that appear throughout the book, all the situations, all the meetings the writer has while he lets time go by waiting for the moment to set himself on fire in front of the Communist Party headquarters, are q</span>
  <span id="freeText3499391149117837836" style="display:none">This is a very interesting book, even though I just rated it with 2 stars. It was written around a very important period of Polish history (last century's eighties), and it is a very interesting and quite realistic (taking everything into account) view of the Communist Poland. All characters that appear throughout the book, all the situations, all the meetings the writer has while he lets time go by waiting for the moment to set himself on fire in front of the Communist Party headquarters, are quite characteristic of the era and as said, it is a vivid representation of Poland.<br /><br />But the book sputters and ends a little bit with a wimp after a good start. The narrator is an intellectual and a little bit of a snob, but Konwicki doesn't fall into making he unlikable. But his adventures during that day in Poland are quite chaotic and the novel loses steam around the middle. It never becomes boring, but doesn't grip either.<br /><br />For people interested in Poland's history and culture, it may be an interesting reading, but it is far from perfect.<br /><br />5,5</span>
  <a data-text-id="3499391149117837836" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


